<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1045,2010]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1343,1369]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[874,996,1344,1369]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amicus">
<emphasis box="[874,996,1344,1369]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. amicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1065,1241,1344,1369]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matricarius">
<emphasis box="[1065,1241,1344,1369]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. matricarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but it is easily distinguished by the upward turning of vein R 
<number box="[690,698,1397,1411]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[708,715,1397,1411]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="5.0">5</number>
so it meets the costa at the level of CuA 
<number box="[1186,1194,1397,1411]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1.0">1</number>
(in 
<taxonomicName box="[1238,1354,1381,1406]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amicus">
<emphasis box="[1238,1354,1381,1406]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. amicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matricarius">E. matricarius</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
vein R 
<number box="[386,395,1437,1451]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[404,412,1437,1451]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="5.0">5</number>
meets the costa much more distal than the level of CuA 
<number box="[1088,1096,1437,1451]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" value="1.0">1</number>
), by the lanceolate shape of antennae (oval in 
<taxonomicName box="[361,477,1462,1487]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amicus">
<emphasis box="[361,477,1462,1487]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. amicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[535,704,1462,1487]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matricarius">
<emphasis box="[535,704,1462,1487]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. matricarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the features of male and female genitalia. In 
<taxonomicName box="[1299,1436,1462,1487]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ebellicus">
<emphasis box="[1299,1436,1462,1487]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. ebellicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the furca has no sclerotization around the genital orifice (well sclerotised around genital orifice in 
<taxonomicName box="[1310,1426,1499,1524]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amicus">
<emphasis box="[1310,1426,1499,1524]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. amicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and spermathecal reservoir has a deep invagination and dark brown bands on the outer surface (spermathecal reservoir with shallow invagination and without bands on outer surface in 
<taxonomicName box="[1087,1268,1574,1599]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matricarius">
<emphasis box="[1087,1268,1574,1599]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. matricarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). In the male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[293,431,1611,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ebellicus">
<emphasis box="[293,431,1611,1636]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. ebellicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the gonostyli is at the apex of gonocoxa and have long and pointed processes (in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amicus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. amicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[292,461,1649,1674]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Empidideicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matricarius">
<emphasis box="[292,461,1649,1674]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">E. matricarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the gonostyli are inserted deeply in the median part of gonocoxa and without any processes).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
